B0$ As a spinner, feels good when the ball is turning and holding. We practise here, we know what's the ideal length and pace. The visiting team needs time to adapt. We are taking advantage of the home conditions. Everyone's doing their job. We are doing a good job collectively. (On batting higher) I keep hearing Mahi bhai's chants. If I bat higher, then the crowd will wait for me to get out. As long as the team wins, I am happy.

formatValue: Ravindra Jadeja | Player of the Match:

commText: B0$ It turned a lot in the second half. We know that our spinners use a lot more seam than some of the other bowlers. We thought it'll slow down. We didn't know what's a good score. That's why I wanted the bowlers to bowl their best deliveries but not look for wickets every delivery. That's when you start not bowling well. I felt 166-170 was a good score. But as a batting unit, we can do better. The good thing is Moeen and Jaddu got a chance to bat. As we get closer to the last phase of the tournament, it's important that everybody has a few deliveries under their belt. We need to be happy with our batting. I would have loved Mitch (Santner), he's a bowler that has done very well on flat wickets with the new ball. He hits the seam and bowls at a good pace. He (Gaikwad) is batting really well, he's somebody once he starts scoring, he's very effortless. He's somebody who's happy to rotate. He has the game awareness. He is ready to adapt. You rarely get people like that. People who read the game, those are the kind of players you need in your team. This is what my job is, I have told them this is what I am supposed to do, don't make me run a lot and it has been working. This is what I need to do, happy to contribute.

commText: B0$ It was swinging nicely and at the same time, the pitch was slow. We thought the wicket would slow down in the 2nd innings and it was cloudy, so no dew - that's why Mahi bhai decided to bat first. 165 was a par score on this track. Powerplay was crucial as the ball comes nicely and we had a great powerplay. It is very difficult with injuries, every time you get injured you start from zero. Still not 100% but trying to do a job to contribute to the team.

B0$ Back to losing three wickets. We lost a wicket in the first over. Our opening combination is crucial. We lost a wicket to a run-out. We threw wickets away. Put too much on pressure on ourselves. Was a gettable total. To sum it up, we needed a better first six. We couldn't rotate strike. We needed to try different things but we couldn't. When you get a wide half-tracker you can't hit it to cover. We should have executed better with those wide half-trackers.

B0$ Classic CSK performance at Chepauk. On a tricky surface, they opted to bat and posted 167 on the board. That turned out to be more than enough for the hosts. Deepak Chahar nipped out both the openers and a horrible mix-up resulted in Marsh's downfall. The visitors had lost their top three inside four overs on a slow surface even before MSD had introduced spin. Manish Pandey and Rossouw stitched a 59-run stand for the fourth wicket but that came at run-a-ball. The CSK spinners choked DC with spin and the visitors couldn't recover after that. Matheesha Pathirana was a touch expensive but he picked three wickets as he coupled his yorkers with the slower deliveries.

commText: B0$ Firstly, it's great to be out there. I didn't start in the team for the first few games, so to come into the side and to put a couple of performances together, I am really happy with that. To win us the game, even happier. You have to get your head around the different conditions and different sorts of wickets, the surfaces you might play on. I made a couple of small technical adjustments but nothing too wholesale, So far so good. I am loving it (tournament), I am taking in as much as I can. We've got an unbelievable coaching staff here. To have Punter and Watto, just to name a couple, is unbelievable for myself. They've played so much cricket, they know so much about the game. It's about trying to get as much as I can out of them everyday. (DC's approach) Every game realistically for us is a final, same as the last game so nothing changes in that regard. The mentality has to be the same. We know Chennai are a very strong side, especially at home. Not many teams come here and win. If we are going to get the points today, we have to go out, play positively and really take it to them.

commText: B0$ They were slow starters. From looking under-cooked, they have been burning on slow flame in the last few games. The addition of Salt at the top has helped as was seen in the last game. They have collected four wins from the last five games. Warner has looked good. Marsh has been a reliable all-rounder. Ishant has had new wings. DC will not be easy pushovers.

B0$ The opening combination for CSK has just added an icing to the legacy that has existed for years now. The chemistry between Ruturaj and Conway has put every Ionic or Covalent bond to shame. Dube's confidence and scores have inflated with every passing game. Deshpande has been one of the finds of the IPL. Pathirana's death bowling has been impeccable.

Everyone thought MI will have to tackle spin but Deepak Chahar and Matheesha Pathirana just outfoxed the opponents. DC don't possess the best players of spin bowling and their batting reserves would be tested by CSK's spin trio. A win for CSK will fortify their place at number 2. And with only a handful of games left, the pole position might as well change hands with every game if CSK continue to be on the heels of GT. DC can't afford a loss. They have picked up momentum but these final gasps would have to be mammoth for them to be in contention for the playoffs. There are four teams on 10 points from 11 games. DC can be the latest entrant. Plot twists make a story look more fascinating. But the twists and turns in this edition have had a reeling impact on fans. No team is still out of contention and no team is certain of a ticket to top four!

B0$ Since the start of IPL 2013 till this season started, only MI (3 times) and PWI had beaten CSK at Chepauk. How do I describe the word 'fortress' in a better manner? They have slipped twice this season. Both games were cliffhangers and could have gone either ways. Sandeep Sharma held his cool against a marauding MS and Liam Livingstone tore into Tushar Deshapande for PBKS. That meant the Chepauk crowd had to witness two losses. But CSK shrugged it off in the last game as they outplayed MI in a thumping manner.

B0$ by B1$ 
 
This is usually that time of the season when the top teams are consolidating their positions and bracing for a Playoffs run. IPL 2023 has proved to be an antithesis to such notions and therefore Michael Hussey was quick to state that his side wasn't pursuing that line of conversation at all. Chennai Super Kings though can see a tiny chasm between themselves and the chasing pack. With two of their three remaining games to be played at home, they will believe they can maintain, maybe even extend, the daylight to the logjam right behind. 
 
Victory against Mumbai Indians, as MS Dhoni conceded, was most opportune. Not only did it create the aforementioned breathing room, it helped arrest a strange, three-game sequence without a win. It would appear that particular game also helped brush the cobwebs off some other arrowheads in their quiver. Deepak Chahar found his PowerPlay efficacy to supplement the team's middle-overs smarts as well as the Pathirana-provided thrust at the death. 
 
Meanwhile, Delhi Capitals too are a team that don't have to peer into the past too much, given how their form has progressively ebbed coming into the pointy end of the league. "Our cricket is absolutely on the improve," exclaimed Ricky Ponting in a dressing room after the cruise past RCB in the last game. After taking five straight Ls, they've won four of their last five and with an all-foreign top-four, appear to have discovered the batting oomph that had been missing for so long. True to the cliche therefore, the points table is unlikely to dictate how this game will play out. This season has taught us that much already. 
 
B2$Chennai Super Kings vs Delhi Capitals, IPL 2023, May 10, 19:30 IST 
 
B3$MA Chidambaram Stadium, Chennai 
 
B4$Sultry evening conditions after a few days of showers in the city. CSK last played a night game on April 27. Chennai last hosted a night game on April 21. So quick re-calibrations will be needed. MS Dhoni wanted to bat first against Mumbai Indians and was out-voted by the rest of the brains trust. Chasing could once more become the more unanimous choice this time around. 
 
B5$CSK 17-10 DC. Chennai's 91-run win over Delhi last year featured a familiar name from the class of 2023: Devon Conway. CSK rode on his 49-ball 87 and defended 208 with ease in Navi Mumbai.

However, at this stage he is only likely to replace Moeen Ali and against a Capitals team that has lost most wickets to spin this season (30 at ER 7.43) and with three key left-handers in the top-six, CSK are unlikely to make that swap for this game.

The challenge for DC however will be to defend against Conway, who has hit left-arm spinners at a strike-rate of 203.85 without once being dismissed by them in this season. Then there's also Shivam Dube, who has a strike-rate of 165.33 against spin.

And we just knew the way he plays, you're just gonna have to be patient because he is fairly high risk with the way he bats. But that also makes him so incredibly dangerous when up and going like, we've seen the games where he scored the runs into the two 50s that he's got, it's against world-class bowling and he's taking him down." - DC Assistant Coach B17$ on the impact of Phil Salt. 
 
"I don't think I've ever been involved in a tournament where the table is so tight. So it would be so dangerous to start looking ahead and start thinking about a final finishing position because if you take your eye off, then we'll get ourselves into trouble. So it's not even been a topic of conversation at all. Obviously, we're dreaming about it [the Playoffs]. And hoping, but there's a lot of hard work to be done before." - CSK batting coach B18$ on casting one eye on the Playoffs.
